1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:12,189
[SPEAKER_10]: In nine days' time, one of the two men standing here will be Prime Minister.

2
00:00:12,390 --> 00:00:14,252
[SPEAKER_10]: Tonight, they go head-to-head.

3
00:00:14,473 --> 00:00:24,688
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome to the BBC Prime Ministerial Debate.

4
00:00:48,867 --> 00:00:50,429
[SPEAKER_10]: Good evening.

5
00:00:50,449 --> 00:00:55,176
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome to Nottingham and to Nottingham Trent University, our venue for this debate.

6
00:00:55,596 --> 00:01:05,450
[SPEAKER_10]: With the general election just over a week away tonight, Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer are about to spend the next hour and a quarter answering voters' questions.

7
00:01:05,830 --> 00:01:08,113
[SPEAKER_10]: They are the two contenders for Prime Minister.

8
00:01:08,394 --> 00:01:13,761
[SPEAKER_10]: Their positions on this debate stage have been decided by the toss of a coin.

9
00:01:13,741 --> 00:01:16,347
[SPEAKER_10]: They do not know what the questions will be.

10
00:01:16,628 --> 00:01:24,226
[SPEAKER_10]: Those will be coming primarily from our live audience here at the University, who have been chosen by the pollsters, Savanta.

11
00:01:24,466 --> 00:01:31,142
[SPEAKER_10]: They include supporters of the Conservatives and of Labour, as well as some undecided voters.

12
00:01:31,122 --> 00:01:37,009
[SPEAKER_10]: And we will also have questions submitted through the BBC's Your Voice, Your Vote website.

13
00:01:37,390 --> 00:01:53,029
[SPEAKER_10]: After 75 minutes of debate, we will have analysis from our Spin Room, which is also here on the Nottingham Trent campus, and that is where Laura Koonsberg and Clive Myrie will be talking to other politicians and also to fellow journalists.

14
00:01:53,009 --> 00:01:58,261
[SPEAKER_10]: And so, to the leaders, Rishi Sunak and Keir Starmer, welcome to you both.

15
00:01:58,382 --> 00:02:02,792
[SPEAKER_10]: It's very good that you're taking part in this with just over a week to polling day.

16
00:02:02,852 --> 00:02:03,894
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome.

17
00:02:04,295 --> 00:02:04,496
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

18
00:02:04,516 --> 00:02:09,347
[SPEAKER_10]: Let us begin straight away with our first question, and it is from Sue Barclay.

19
00:02:12,128 --> 00:02:17,194
[SPEAKER_09]: People are dismayed by the lack of integrity and honesty in politics today.

20
00:02:18,275 --> 00:02:24,563
[SPEAKER_09]: After the recent allegations about political betting, how would you restore trust in politics?

21
00:02:26,085 --> 00:02:28,568
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much, Sue, for kicking us off.

22
00:02:28,588 --> 00:02:33,113
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, both of your parties have faced allegations in this regard in recent days.

23
00:02:33,153 --> 00:02:36,757
[SPEAKER_10]: We know of five Conservatives being investigated and one Labour.

24
00:02:37,238 --> 00:02:38,119
[SPEAKER_10]: Rishi Sunak.

25
00:02:38,437 --> 00:02:40,860
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, Sue, I completely share your anger.

26
00:02:40,901 --> 00:02:45,327
[SPEAKER_04]: I was as frustrated as you are furious when I learnt about these allegations.

27
00:02:45,787 --> 00:02:55,581
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why, alongside the Gambling Commission, we initiated our own internal inquiries into what had happened and, as a result of that, have suspended two candidates.

28
00:02:55,682 --> 00:02:57,003
[SPEAKER_04]: And I've been crystal clear.

29
00:02:57,344 --> 00:03:05,415
[SPEAKER_04]: Anyone who has broken the law, broken the rules, should not only face the full consequences of the law, I will ensure that they're booted out of the Conservative Party.

30
00:03:05,856 --> 00:03:06,537
[SPEAKER_10]: Keir Starmer?

31
00:03:06,517 --> 00:03:13,945
[SPEAKER_03]: Sue, thank you very much for your question, which I think is on a lot of people's minds, this question of respect and integrity in politics.

32
00:03:14,325 --> 00:03:16,928
[SPEAKER_03]: And you have to lead from the front on issues like this.

33
00:03:17,188 --> 00:03:25,337
[SPEAKER_03]: I think over the last 14 years, politics has become too much about self-entitlement and MPs thinking about what they can get for themselves.

34
00:03:25,977 --> 00:03:36,068
[SPEAKER_03]: And one of the important choices, and the thing that I would like to do if I'm elected Prime Minister, is to reset politics so that politics returns to public service.

35
00:03:36,048 --> 00:03:47,587
[SPEAKER_03]: In relation to these gambling allegations, the instinct of these people to think the first thing they should do is try to make money was the wrong instinct and we have to change that.

36
00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:55,381
[SPEAKER_03]: But it is also a question of leadership because this isn't just, you know, what's happened this week, last week in the Gambling Commission.

37
00:03:55,401 --> 00:03:58,265
[SPEAKER_03]: We saw Partygate earlier in this Parliament.

38
00:03:58,285 --> 00:03:59,828
[SPEAKER_03]: The Prime Minister himself

39
00:03:59,808 --> 00:04:05,778
[SPEAKER_03]: was convicted and fined for breaking the rules which he brought in and imposed on everybody else.

40
00:04:05,798 --> 00:04:10,987
[SPEAKER_03]: And of course, we've seen what happened with the COVID contracts and the huge amounts of money that were made.

41
00:04:11,227 --> 00:04:12,189
[SPEAKER_03]: This takes leadership.

42
00:04:12,389 --> 00:04:23,368
[SPEAKER_03]: What I did when one of my team was alleged to have been involved and investigated by the Gambling Commission, they were suspended within minutes because I knew it made it really important to be swift.

43
00:04:23,348 --> 00:04:30,348
[SPEAKER_03]: the Prime Minister delayed and delayed and delayed until eventually he was a bullied into taking action.

44
00:04:30,368 --> 00:04:36,003
[SPEAKER_10]: Let me get a response, let me get a response Keir Starmer to those accusations.

45
00:04:36,064 --> 00:04:38,370
[SPEAKER_04]: Well it was important to me that

46
00:04:38,350 --> 00:04:43,495
[SPEAKER_04]: given the seriousness and the sensitivity of the matters at hand, that they were dealt with properly.

47
00:04:43,876 --> 00:04:44,597
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's what I've done.

48
00:04:44,917 --> 00:04:54,567
[SPEAKER_04]: We had an independent internal inquiry into what happened, have taken action and suspended the candidates involved, and I've been crystal clear that they should face the full consequences of the law.

49
00:04:54,587 --> 00:04:57,130
[SPEAKER_04]: But Keir Starmer talks about leadership in politics.

50
00:04:57,150 --> 00:04:58,431
[SPEAKER_04]: That's what Sue's question was about.

51
00:04:58,491 --> 00:05:00,493
[SPEAKER_04]: It was a broad question about how to do that.

52
00:05:00,894 --> 00:05:04,037
[SPEAKER_04]: I also think leadership means being straight with people.

53
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:12,558
[SPEAKER_04]: It means having the courage of your convictions, not changing your mind on every single position that you've taken, and being upfront about what you want to do for the country.

54
00:05:12,819 --> 00:05:14,463
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not what Keir Starmer is doing.

55
00:05:14,703 --> 00:05:17,970
[SPEAKER_04]: He's not being honest with everyone about his plans to raise their taxes.

56
00:05:18,091 --> 00:05:20,035
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that will erode trust in politics.

57
00:05:20,015 --> 00:05:20,876
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's the choice at this election.

58
00:05:20,916 --> 00:05:28,268
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's just stick to the heart of the question, first of all, because it was sparked by the recent allegations about political betting, and Sue asked how you would restore trust in politics.

59
00:05:28,288 --> 00:05:35,560
[SPEAKER_10]: So if you've acted now to withdraw support from those two Conservative candidates, what did you find in that investigation?

60
00:05:35,540 --> 00:05:42,508
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, Bashar, you know there's an independent investigation which is ongoing, which is why I can't say anything further about that.

61
00:05:42,588 --> 00:05:43,429
[SPEAKER_04]: You will understand that.

62
00:05:43,449 --> 00:05:44,470
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, but we knew about that one a while ago.

63
00:05:44,490 --> 00:05:51,097
[SPEAKER_04]: But when we had our internal inquiries, when we found things that were not appropriate, I took action and suspended the candidates.

64
00:05:51,117 --> 00:05:51,978
[SPEAKER_04]: I've been crystal clear.

65
00:05:52,339 --> 00:05:54,261
[SPEAKER_04]: I was furious to hear about these things.

66
00:05:54,401 --> 00:05:55,342
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why I've dealt with it.

67
00:05:55,682 --> 00:06:00,788
[SPEAKER_04]: But the choice of this election is about, as Sue said, it's about leadership, it's about integrity in politics.

68
00:06:00,768 --> 00:06:02,551
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's a question about doing what you say.

69
00:06:03,432 --> 00:06:09,001
[SPEAKER_04]: Keir Starmer's made this broader point, but the point is he's changed his mind on every major position that he's taken.

70
00:06:09,322 --> 00:06:16,313
[SPEAKER_04]: He doesn't have the courage of his convictions and is not being straight with everybody now about his plans if he wins power to raise people's taxes.

71
00:06:16,514 --> 00:06:20,921
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not going to do anything to restore trust in politics, and that's a choice for everyone at this election.

72
00:06:21,181 --> 00:06:27,231
[SPEAKER_04]: Continue tax cuts with the Conservatives or Keir Starmer's tax rises, which he is not being straight with everyone about.

73
00:06:27,211 --> 00:06:36,333
[SPEAKER_10]: Again, to return to the question, Keir Starmer, the Labour candidate from whom you've withdrawn support appears to have betted on losing his own election.

74
00:06:36,895 --> 00:06:40,343
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you know if any other candidate has placed similar bets in this campaign?

75
00:06:40,424 --> 00:06:47,381
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, he was, as you say, investigated by the gambling commission because he bets on himself to lose.

76
00:06:47,762 --> 00:06:51,631
[SPEAKER_03]: As soon as the commission said they were investigating, I suspended him.

77
00:06:52,393 --> 00:06:57,204
[SPEAKER_03]: And I've made very clear to my candidates that I expect high standards in politics.

78
00:06:57,565 --> 00:06:58,888
[SPEAKER_03]: I said last week

79
00:06:58,868 --> 00:07:01,054
[SPEAKER_03]: that the Prime Minister should have taken decisive action.

80
00:07:01,255 --> 00:07:09,538
[SPEAKER_03]: And I said last week, should one of my candidates be investigated by the Commission, then they would be suspended and their feet wouldn't leave the floor.

81
00:07:09,859 --> 00:07:10,761
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's what I did.

82
00:07:10,862 --> 00:07:13,890
[SPEAKER_03]: And so my candidates know I expect the highest standards.

83
00:07:13,870 --> 00:07:17,595
[SPEAKER_03]: and that I'll take decisive action if they fall below those standards.

84
00:07:17,615 --> 00:07:18,276
[SPEAKER_03]: But do you know that...

85
00:07:18,296 --> 00:07:18,897
[SPEAKER_03]: I am... Back to Sue's point.

86
00:07:18,917 --> 00:07:19,318
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you know...

87
00:07:19,498 --> 00:07:23,724
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm absolutely determined... OK. ..to return politics to public service.

88
00:07:23,804 --> 00:07:26,889
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you know that none of your other candidates have placed similar bets?

89
00:07:26,909 --> 00:07:28,611
[SPEAKER_03]: That integrity in public service is so important for our country.

90
00:07:28,632 --> 00:07:31,035
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you know that none of your other candidates have placed similar bets?

91
00:07:31,218 --> 00:07:40,366
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I've made clear to my candidates what the standards are, and they've seen by my actions what the consequences are if they fall short of those standards.

92
00:07:40,386 --> 00:07:42,588
[SPEAKER_03]: But the Prime Minister hides behind a process.

93
00:07:42,949 --> 00:07:46,412
[SPEAKER_03]: He could have taken decisive action last week, even the week before.

94
00:07:46,672 --> 00:07:50,355
[SPEAKER_03]: But he eventually got round to it when he was bullied by other people into doing it.

95
00:07:50,515 --> 00:07:51,556
[SPEAKER_03]: That's not leadership.

96
00:07:51,756 --> 00:07:53,058
[SPEAKER_03]: And he talks about integrity.

97
00:07:53,218 --> 00:08:01,225
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sorry, when you get convicted for breaking the COVID rules, which you imposed on the rest of the country, you really shouldn't be talking about integrity.

98
00:08:01,205 --> 00:08:02,587
[SPEAKER_03]: and politics.

99
00:08:02,907 --> 00:08:06,052
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, leadership means being straight with people about what you plan to do.

100
00:08:07,033 --> 00:08:13,221
[SPEAKER_04]: I've set out my plans clearly, and I appreciate, actually, that not everyone's going to agree with me on everything, but at least you know where I stand.

101
00:08:13,742 --> 00:08:17,507
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, Keir Starmer is not being straight with you about his plans to raise your taxes.

102
00:08:17,868 --> 00:08:19,029
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't think that's leadership.

103
00:08:19,269 --> 00:08:24,777
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't think that people should surrender their family finances to the Labour Party, and that's the choice for people at this election.

104
00:08:24,837 --> 00:08:30,064
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, let me just address that, if I may, because we have set out in our manifesto all of our plans.

105
00:08:30,044 --> 00:08:39,222
[SPEAKER_03]: They're fully funded, they're fully costed and we've set out that we will not be increasing income tax, national insurance or VAT.

106
00:08:39,763 --> 00:08:52,187
[SPEAKER_03]: What the Prime Minister is doing, he's got a manifesto that's got promises to you and everybody watching which are unfunded because his Chancellor has said that the money he's relying on has already been spent.

107
00:08:52,167 --> 00:08:55,013
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, that is the mistake that Liz Truss made.

108
00:08:55,534 --> 00:09:06,015
[SPEAKER_03]: That's what cost so many people so much across this country, and now we've got to repeat unfunded commitments, lots of promises, promises, promises, promises, but where's the money coming from?

109
00:09:06,055 --> 00:09:10,364
[SPEAKER_03]: The Chancellor himself has said the money was spent last year, it isn't available.

110
00:09:10,585 --> 00:09:13,230
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a... And if there's five more years of this... OK.

111
00:09:13,210 --> 00:09:21,360
[SPEAKER_03]: We're going to have the same as we've got now, a cost of living crisis bearing down on people across this country, really struggling because the economy is broken.

112
00:09:21,400 --> 00:09:28,048
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is the chance at this election to turn the page and start to rebuild our country with a stable economy.

113
00:09:28,489 --> 00:09:39,522
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Misha, just to build on it, what the Chancellor did this morning was ask his opposite number, Keir Starmer's shadow Chancellor, to rule out raising all your taxes beyond what they've already announced in the first budget.

114
00:09:39,502 --> 00:09:41,686
[SPEAKER_04]: and the Shadow Chancellor wasn't able to do that today.

115
00:09:41,987 --> 00:09:44,532
[SPEAKER_04]: That's what the Chancellor did today, but you don't have to listen to me.

116
00:09:45,133 --> 00:09:58,641
[SPEAKER_04]: Just go online, go to the Telegraph website, because we've just found a recording that they have put out there from the Deputy Chancellor from the Labour Party admitting that their plans will cost hundreds of billions of pounds.

117
00:09:58,621 --> 00:10:01,625
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm just going to explain something to anyone who hasn't seen this today.

118
00:10:01,645 --> 00:10:04,288
[SPEAKER_04]: That is going to cost all of you thousands of pounds of tax rises.

119
00:10:04,368 --> 00:10:07,652
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why I say Keir Starmer and the Labour Party are not being straight with you.

120
00:10:07,932 --> 00:10:10,035
[SPEAKER_04]: So do not surrender to their tax rises.

121
00:10:10,095 --> 00:10:11,296
[SPEAKER_10]: Let me just explain.

122
00:10:11,336 --> 00:10:23,110
[SPEAKER_10]: This is a reference to Darren Jones, the Shadow Chief Secretary to the Treasury, one of your senior Treasury team, who in a recording given to the Daily Telegraph has said decarbonising the British economy will cost hundreds of billions of pounds.

123
00:10:23,090 --> 00:10:35,162
[SPEAKER_03]: We've set out in our manifesto what we want to do to go to renewable energy, and we've set out how much that will cost, exactly how much is going to be put in, and we've got a column saying how that's going to be funded.

124
00:10:35,702 --> 00:10:48,895
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, it is absolutely right that we want to get in investors to come alongside that government money, and we've been talking, you won't be surprised to learn this, to global investors for the best part of two years.

125
00:10:48,875 --> 00:11:00,365
[SPEAKER_03]: to say that if we put down this money set out in our manifesto, will you come alongside it and put down many more billions of pounds so that in partnership with the government we can make the change that we need?

126
00:11:01,006 --> 00:11:01,787
[SPEAKER_03]: Hang on, hang on.

127
00:11:01,907 --> 00:11:03,068
[SPEAKER_03]: Let me just finish this.

128
00:11:03,188 --> 00:11:05,630
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sure we're going to come back to the same thing later on.

129
00:11:06,251 --> 00:11:07,812
[SPEAKER_03]: This is your own shadow Chancellor.

130
00:11:07,872 --> 00:11:10,755
[SPEAKER_03]: If you don't mind, I'm going to get to the next question.

131
00:11:10,775 --> 00:11:12,176
[SPEAKER_03]: Just be straight with the people.

132
00:11:12,636 --> 00:11:13,737
[SPEAKER_03]: How many hundreds is it?

133
00:11:13,757 --> 00:11:14,598
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it 200?

134
00:11:14,638 --> 00:11:15,879
[SPEAKER_03]: Is it 300?

135
00:11:15,979 --> 00:11:16,660
[SPEAKER_03]: Is it 400?

136
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:18,882
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the Prime Minister must have put a bet on how many times

137
00:11:18,862 --> 00:11:20,604
[SPEAKER_03]: going to interrupt me.

138
00:11:20,624 --> 00:11:25,471
[SPEAKER_10]: I do want to turn to the next question because lots of people are waiting and they've got important questions that they would like answers to.

139
00:11:25,851 --> 00:11:35,584
[SPEAKER_10]: If you can hear any noises off, ladies and gentlemen or anyone at home, there is a protest taking place outside which is also an aspect of our democracy and people exercising their freedom of speech.

140
00:11:35,604 --> 00:11:37,887
[SPEAKER_10]: Our next question here comes from Mary Armstrong.

141
00:11:39,289 --> 00:11:40,110
[SPEAKER_11]: Evening.

142
00:11:40,816 --> 00:11:45,083
[SPEAKER_11]: I've worked two jobs since I was 18, and I'm now 60.

143
00:11:45,123 --> 00:11:53,517
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think too many people don't understand how important and better it is for you to be working hard.

144
00:11:54,278 --> 00:11:57,624
[SPEAKER_11]: I also think too many people are on out-of-work benefits.

145
00:11:58,245 --> 00:12:06,098
[SPEAKER_11]: My question is, what are you going to do to help more people to come off benefits and back into work?

146
00:12:06,078 --> 00:12:08,222
[SPEAKER_10]: Mary, thank you very much for that.

147
00:12:08,342 --> 00:12:12,831
[SPEAKER_10]: Keir Starmer, what are you going to do to get more people off work, off benefits and into work?

148
00:12:12,951 --> 00:12:21,808
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, can I first agree with you that work is, of course, about pay and being able to pay your own way and, you know, support your family.

149
00:12:21,788 --> 00:12:25,233
[SPEAKER_03]: But it is also about dignity and respect.

150
00:12:25,353 --> 00:12:27,576
[SPEAKER_03]: And my dad worked in a factory all his life.

151
00:12:27,596 --> 00:12:28,537
[SPEAKER_03]: He was a toolmaker.

152
00:12:28,977 --> 00:12:34,685
[SPEAKER_03]: And having a secure job for him was really important to his respect and integrity.

153
00:12:34,725 --> 00:12:39,191
[SPEAKER_03]: In relation to those that are out of work, my rule is this.

154
00:12:39,291 --> 00:12:40,753
[SPEAKER_03]: If you can work, you should work.

155
00:12:41,233 --> 00:12:46,320
[SPEAKER_03]: And we've got a plan to get people into work, working with businesses to support people in.

156
00:12:46,601 --> 00:12:49,264
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we need to change the job centre.

157
00:12:49,244 --> 00:12:57,078
[SPEAKER_03]: and the career service, because at the moment, when I ask businesses, if you have a vacancy, are you going to the job centre to get that vacancy filled?

158
00:12:57,098 --> 00:12:58,982
[SPEAKER_03]: They say they're not, so we need to do that.

159
00:12:59,282 --> 00:13:09,902
[SPEAKER_03]: The other thing, Mary, that we absolutely need to do is to get the waiting lists down in the NHS, because very many people aren't able to work or to work in the way they want.

160
00:13:09,882 --> 00:13:15,967
[SPEAKER_03]: because they're waiting for an operation because of the catastrophic level of waiting lists under this government.

161
00:13:16,008 --> 00:13:21,873
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's hear your first response, Rishi Sunak, to Mary's question.

162
00:13:22,273 --> 00:13:24,515
[SPEAKER_10]: What are you going to do to get people off benefits?

163
00:13:24,535 --> 00:13:30,020
[SPEAKER_04]: Mary, there's a clear choice for you and everyone who believes, like you do, the situation isn't right.

164
00:13:30,260 --> 00:13:33,964
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if you want lower taxes and lower welfare, that's what I'll deliver.

165
00:13:33,984 --> 00:13:37,167
[SPEAKER_04]: If you want higher taxes and higher welfare, that's what Keir Starmer will do.

166
00:13:37,187 --> 00:13:39,889
[SPEAKER_04]: So I strongly agree that people are better off in work.

167
00:13:39,869 --> 00:13:48,104
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not just for the financial security it brings you, it's about the purpose, the dignity that it brings to people which you alluded to and I strongly agree with.

168
00:13:48,705 --> 00:13:52,532
[SPEAKER_04]: The number of people currently out of work on ill health and disability benefits is too high.

169
00:13:53,254 --> 00:13:57,321
[SPEAKER_04]: It's gone up by 800,000 since the pandemic, it's gone up by 60% the bill.

170
00:13:57,301 --> 00:13:58,343
[SPEAKER_04]: in the last few years.

171
00:13:58,583 --> 00:13:59,966
[SPEAKER_04]: We've got to do something about that.

172
00:14:00,287 --> 00:14:01,950
[SPEAKER_04]: I made a speech about this a few months ago.

173
00:14:02,331 --> 00:14:09,064
