00:36:24,625 --> 00:36:29,654
[SPEAKER_04]: I'll ask him again, but I'm going to tell you, do not surrender your family finances to Labour's tax rises.

536
00:36:29,674 --> 00:36:39,572
[SPEAKER_03]: Let me address this directly, because the Prime Minister said he warned the country about Liz Truss and the damage that she was going to do to our economy.

537
00:36:39,974 --> 00:36:43,783
[SPEAKER_03]: And then in the next breath, he said, we must unite behind her and support her.

538
00:36:43,843 --> 00:36:46,789
[SPEAKER_03]: Why on earth would you unite behind someone that you say was going to do that damage?

539
00:36:46,829 --> 00:36:49,896
[SPEAKER_10]: Hang on, you know what it's like to fall in behind a leader of your party.

540
00:36:49,916 --> 00:36:52,101
[SPEAKER_03]: But he's repeating the problem.

541
00:36:55,569 --> 00:36:56,110
[SPEAKER_03]: He's repeating the problem.

542
00:36:56,984 --> 00:36:59,006
[SPEAKER_03]: Who said unite behind her?

543
00:36:59,026 --> 00:37:00,387
[SPEAKER_03]: She's one of his candidates.

544
00:37:00,407 --> 00:37:09,535
[SPEAKER_03]: And his election pitch to you seems to be, my predecessor, a Tory Prime Minister, broke the country, did huge economic damage.

545
00:37:10,196 --> 00:37:11,117
[SPEAKER_03]: Please vote Tory.

546
00:37:11,897 --> 00:37:14,019
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, you're going to have to decide whether that's persuasive.

547
00:37:14,320 --> 00:37:20,245
[SPEAKER_03]: He's now openly admitting the damage that the Tories have done to the economy and saying, please vote for him.

548
00:37:20,906 --> 00:37:23,348
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the last thing we need in this country after the damage that's been done.

549
00:37:23,368 --> 00:37:24,469
[SPEAKER_03]: My pitch is straightforward.

550
00:37:24,489 --> 00:37:26,991
[SPEAKER_04]: When it comes to the economy, I was right then.

551
00:37:26,971 --> 00:37:38,010
[SPEAKER_04]: And since I've been your Prime Minister, inflation is back to normal, the economy is growing faster than our competitors, wages are rising, energy bills are falling, we've started cutting your taxes and I will keep cutting your taxes.

552
00:37:38,351 --> 00:37:44,201
[SPEAKER_04]: That is my pitch to you, that's a choice at this election, their taxes that he wants to put up on you are coming.

553
00:37:44,522 --> 00:37:48,068
[SPEAKER_04]: He won't rule out revaluing your council tax bands, every pensioner

554
00:37:48,048 --> 00:37:58,143
[SPEAKER_04]: that is watching should realise that under a future Labour government, for the first time in our country's history, the state pension will be subject to a retirement tax under Labour.

555
00:37:58,443 --> 00:37:59,545
[SPEAKER_04]: That's what their plans are.

556
00:37:59,785 --> 00:38:01,067
[SPEAKER_04]: Those are the numbers, black and white.

557
00:38:01,367 --> 00:38:02,169
[SPEAKER_04]: We're not going to do that.

558
00:38:02,189 --> 00:38:03,410
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to have the triple lock plus.

559
00:38:03,631 --> 00:38:10,781
[SPEAKER_04]: But for the millions of pensioners that are watching, be very worried, because you're going to face a retirement tax under the Labour Party.

560
00:38:10,861 --> 00:38:12,844
[SPEAKER_03]: Don't insult people by putting out falsehoods.

561
00:38:12,924 --> 00:38:14,507
[SPEAKER_10]: Just don't insult people by putting out falsehoods.

562
00:38:14,527 --> 00:38:15,007
[SPEAKER_10]: You mentioned the IFS.

563
00:38:15,027 --> 00:38:15,448
[SPEAKER_10]: Which ones are false?

564
00:38:15,468 --> 00:38:16,890
[SPEAKER_03]: He keeps saying we're going to raise taxes.

565
00:38:16,870 --> 00:38:18,353
[SPEAKER_04]: Can you confirm...

566
00:38:18,373 --> 00:38:20,556
[SPEAKER_04]: He obviously has put a bet on interrupting me, hasn't he?

567
00:38:20,777 --> 00:38:24,263
[SPEAKER_04]: ..will the state pension be subject to income tax under a future Labour government?

568
00:38:24,283 --> 00:38:27,108
[SPEAKER_04]: The only way for it not is for you to match our triple lot plus.

569
00:38:27,328 --> 00:38:28,931
[SPEAKER_04]: So maybe you can change policy here tonight.

570
00:38:29,211 --> 00:38:33,259
[SPEAKER_04]: Will you match our triple lot plus and ensure that state pension is never subject to income tax?

571
00:38:33,439 --> 00:38:33,900
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes or no?

572
00:38:34,120 --> 00:38:38,007
[SPEAKER_03]: The position on the state pension that we've set out is exactly...

573
00:38:38,027 --> 00:38:38,808
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a yes or no?

574
00:38:38,828 --> 00:38:40,431
[SPEAKER_10]: Hang on, we need to hear this response.

575
00:38:40,782 --> 00:38:47,714
[SPEAKER_03]: I think you should show some respect to the audience who want to know what I've got to say about this without constantly being interrupted.

576
00:38:48,115 --> 00:38:49,598
[SPEAKER_03]: It really isn't the way to do the debate.

577
00:38:49,678 --> 00:38:52,763
[SPEAKER_10]: What's the answer to the question about whether you'll match what they're going to do on pensions?

578
00:38:52,783 --> 00:39:00,136
[SPEAKER_03]: On this question, the position on pensioners and tax or pensions on tax that we've set out is exactly the same.

579
00:39:00,237 --> 00:39:03,222
[SPEAKER_03]: It is the position of the government at their last budget.

580
00:39:03,242 --> 00:39:04,444
[SPEAKER_03]: It is their position.

581
00:39:04,424 --> 00:39:06,688
[SPEAKER_03]: The Prime Minister now says, oh, I'm going to change that.

582
00:39:07,108 --> 00:39:08,170
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm going to change all that.

583
00:39:08,491 --> 00:39:12,397
[SPEAKER_03]: When asked where the money is coming from, his Chancellor says the money that's being spent, it isn't there.

584
00:39:12,537 --> 00:39:14,481
[SPEAKER_03]: That is making the same mistake again.

585
00:39:14,641 --> 00:39:17,325
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I just address the IFS point, though, because I think that is really important.

586
00:39:17,345 --> 00:39:17,966
[SPEAKER_03]: Everybody heard that.

587
00:39:17,986 --> 00:39:24,998
[SPEAKER_04]: If you're a pensioner, you should know there is a retirement tax coming for you, capital R, capital T, if he is your Prime Minister.

588
00:39:24,978 --> 00:39:31,631
[SPEAKER_04]: For the first time in our country's history, pensioners are going to be paying tax because he won't match our triple lock plus.

589
00:39:31,831 --> 00:39:33,975
[SPEAKER_04]: If I'm your Prime Minister, that won't happen.

590
00:39:34,236 --> 00:39:35,518
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's what I'll deliver for you.

591
00:39:35,578 --> 00:39:39,105
[SPEAKER_04]: As I say it again, do not surrender your finances to their tax rises.

592
00:39:39,125 --> 00:39:40,348
[SPEAKER_10]: I think you've got a very brief response.

593
00:39:40,368 --> 00:39:41,670
[SPEAKER_10]: Then I want to go to the next question.

594
00:39:41,802 --> 00:39:47,572
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, pensioners are not going to be better off with a Prime Minister who's making promises that he can't keep because they're not funded.

595
00:39:47,592 --> 00:39:49,616
[SPEAKER_03]: That's exactly what Liz Truss got wrong.

596
00:39:49,997 --> 00:39:53,062
[SPEAKER_03]: There's one thing that we cannot repeat at this election.

597
00:39:53,262 --> 00:39:59,153
[SPEAKER_03]: Please do not go back to Liz Truss mark two with this Prime Minister because the same damage will follow.

598
00:39:59,133 --> 00:40:00,455
[SPEAKER_03]: It is funded.

599
00:40:00,535 --> 00:40:01,297
[SPEAKER_03]: It is funded.

600
00:40:01,357 --> 00:40:04,663
[SPEAKER_05]: We're going to end this particular topic here.

601
00:40:04,683 --> 00:40:07,688
[SPEAKER_04]: The reason you can't fund it is because you think that you can't fund it.

602
00:40:07,708 --> 00:40:08,429
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Singapore.

603
00:40:08,489 --> 00:40:09,932
[SPEAKER_05]: We've still got lots of topics to get through.

604
00:40:09,992 --> 00:40:11,254
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'm going to turn to the next question.

605
00:40:11,274 --> 00:40:12,296
[SPEAKER_05]: That's why you can't fund it.

606
00:40:12,316 --> 00:40:13,218
[SPEAKER_10]: That's why I can.

607
00:40:13,238 --> 00:40:13,638
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

608
00:40:13,719 --> 00:40:16,804
[SPEAKER_10]: This next question is from Karen Duran.

609
00:40:18,168 --> 00:40:18,649
[SPEAKER_12]: Good evening.

610
00:40:18,989 --> 00:40:21,372
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm a children's nurse at a local hospital.

611
00:40:22,033 --> 00:40:26,097
[SPEAKER_12]: I see families affected by libraries and children's centres closing.

612
00:40:26,798 --> 00:40:32,885
[SPEAKER_12]: How will you help councils after Nottingham City Council has effectively gone bankrupt?

613
00:40:33,807 --> 00:40:34,608
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Karen.

614
00:40:40,915 --> 00:40:44,099
[SPEAKER_10]: And the council here has been run by Labour since 1991.

615
00:40:45,180 --> 00:40:45,981
[SPEAKER_10]: Keir Starmer.

616
00:40:46,501 --> 00:40:57,422
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, and I'm very concerned about the situation because I think anybody looking at a council which has run out of money is concerned about the basic services, whether it's libraries or other support that councils have to put in place.

617
00:40:57,571 --> 00:41:01,475
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is a position for councils of all political stripes.

618
00:41:01,495 --> 00:41:09,702
[SPEAKER_03]: There are Conservative-run councils that have struggled for money and gone bankrupt as well because of the lack of adequate and proper structured funding from the government.

619
00:41:09,722 --> 00:41:15,167
[SPEAKER_03]: You asked what we would do about it, and I think it is important for us to set out what we would do if we came into office.

620
00:41:15,487 --> 00:41:17,989
[SPEAKER_03]: We would change the way the payments are made to councils.

621
00:41:18,029 --> 00:41:24,315
[SPEAKER_03]: At the moment, council leaders are saying they're made on a yearly basis, so we can't make the most effective use of the money that's available to us.

622
00:41:24,595 --> 00:41:27,578
[SPEAKER_03]: If they're on longer term, we could make much better use of that.

623
00:41:27,558 --> 00:41:38,331
[SPEAKER_03]: Secondly, they're saying if you could do what the Conservatives promised but didn't actually do, which is to stop no-fault evictions, that would have a massive help for councils as well.

624
00:41:38,351 --> 00:41:44,158
[SPEAKER_03]: Because when people lose their home through no fault of their own, quite a lot of them end up having to have support of a local authority.

625
00:41:44,378 --> 00:41:46,000
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think you should have no-fault evictions.

626
00:41:46,320 --> 00:41:48,303
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we should actually get on and get rid of them.

627
00:41:48,343 --> 00:41:49,704
[SPEAKER_03]: That's what the Prime Minister used to say, but he doesn't do it.

628
00:41:49,724 --> 00:41:54,510
[SPEAKER_10]: But on your point about council funding, a multi-year funding plan doesn't give more money, necessarily.

629
00:41:54,490 --> 00:42:00,241
[SPEAKER_10]: Are you saying there is more money that would come to local authorities under a Labour government?

630
00:42:00,321 --> 00:42:10,240
[SPEAKER_03]: If you go for a three-year settlement it means the available money can be used better because any council leader will tell you that trying to make the best use of the money within the constraints of a 12-month period doesn't work.

631
00:42:10,380 --> 00:42:12,043
[SPEAKER_03]: So it's better use of existing money.

632
00:42:12,023 --> 00:42:19,414
[SPEAKER_03]: But look, I'm not going to stand here and say there's some magic wand that I can wave the day after the election and find money that isn't there.

633
00:42:19,575 --> 00:42:22,118
[SPEAKER_03]: Huge damage has been done to our economy.

634
00:42:22,299 --> 00:42:23,420
[SPEAKER_03]: It is going to take time.

635
00:42:23,641 --> 00:42:33,576
[SPEAKER_03]: That's why our manifesto is a manifesto for growing our economy, for creating wealth, to making sure that we can make sure all of our public services, whether that's councils or others,

636
00:42:33,556 --> 00:42:39,986
[SPEAKER_03]: are properly funded, providing the services that people expect and actually, frankly, deserve, which is not the case at the moment.

637
00:42:40,007 --> 00:42:40,988
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's get Rishi Sunak's response.

638
00:42:41,008 --> 00:42:44,574
[SPEAKER_10]: How will you help councils after Nottingham City Council has effectively gone bankrupt?

639
00:42:44,714 --> 00:42:51,345
[SPEAKER_04]: Karen, my first job in government was being local government minister, so I was responsible for councils, and they do an extraordinary job.

640
00:42:51,325 --> 00:42:55,493
[SPEAKER_04]: And much as people focus on national politics, actually, most politics is local.

641
00:42:55,533 --> 00:42:58,518
[SPEAKER_04]: It's what's happening in your street, your neighborhood, your community.

642
00:42:58,879 --> 00:43:04,188
[SPEAKER_04]: And the services that you mentioned are so important, particularly those that concern families and children.

643
00:43:04,569 --> 00:43:07,815
[SPEAKER_04]: One of the things that I do want to do is actually roll out family hubs.

644
00:43:07,795 --> 00:43:15,445
[SPEAKER_04]: as we've been doing over the past few years, which are special places where whole families can come and get the advice and support they need, particularly the most vulnerable families.

645
00:43:15,806 --> 00:43:26,921
[SPEAKER_04]: Again, in terms of funding councils, we've recently announced just over half a billion pounds of extra funding for councils, particularly for social care, which is where some of the big pressures are, and children's services, which you alluded to.

646
00:43:26,961 --> 00:43:30,445
[SPEAKER_04]: And we'll continue to work with councils to provide them the support they need.

647
00:43:30,726 --> 00:43:32,508
[SPEAKER_04]: But you mentioned Nottingham, right?

648
00:43:32,528 --> 00:43:34,731
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is a glimpse of the future.

649
00:43:34,711 --> 00:43:37,658
[SPEAKER_04]: Nottingham City Council bankrupt under Labour.

650
00:43:37,899 --> 00:43:50,070
[SPEAKER_04]: Birmingham City Council, the largest council in the country, in fact the largest in Europe, not just bankrupt but as a result everyone in Birmingham is now paying a 20% higher council tax bill.

651
00:43:50,050 --> 00:43:54,416
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is a snapshot of what will happen if Keir Starmer is in power across the country.

652
00:43:54,596 --> 00:44:05,252
[SPEAKER_04]: As Labour always do, they run out of everyone's money, they bankrupt the economy in 2010, they bankrupted Birmingham, they bankrupted Nottingham, and that's why everyone in Birmingham is paying a 20% higher council tax.

653
00:44:05,272 --> 00:44:10,479
[SPEAKER_04]: So that is just an appetiser of the higher taxes that are going to come under a future Labour government.

654
00:44:10,679 --> 00:44:14,725
[SPEAKER_04]: Do not surrender your local council and our finances to them.

655
00:44:14,890 --> 00:44:20,039
[SPEAKER_10]: Councils like Working and Thurrock were conservative when similar problems first emerged.

656
00:44:20,059 --> 00:44:20,680
[SPEAKER_03]: What do you say about that?

657
00:44:20,740 --> 00:44:23,044
[SPEAKER_03]: Conservative councils in exactly the same problem.

658
00:44:23,064 --> 00:44:23,786
[SPEAKER_03]: What do you say about that?

659
00:44:24,146 --> 00:44:30,978
[SPEAKER_03]: I have to say, a Prime Minister gloating about the fact that councils are struggling and the impact that you know of, he's responsible for gloating.

660
00:44:30,998 --> 00:44:34,705
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to believe me, you can go and check as a result of their financial mismanagement.

661
00:44:34,685 --> 00:44:37,350
[SPEAKER_04]: The same thing happened in Nottingham, right?

662
00:44:37,370 --> 00:44:38,992
[SPEAKER_04]: That's what you get with the Labour Party.

663
00:44:39,012 --> 00:44:41,457
[SPEAKER_04]: You remember what happened last time they were in office?

664
00:44:41,697 --> 00:44:46,185
[SPEAKER_04]: They run out of your money, they bankrupt the country, and you all pay for it in higher taxes.

665
00:44:46,285 --> 00:44:48,389
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the choice for you at this election.

666
00:44:48,930 --> 00:44:50,032
[SPEAKER_04]: We are making progress.

667
00:44:50,072 --> 00:44:51,454
[SPEAKER_04]: The economy is growing.

668
00:44:51,694 --> 00:44:53,217
[SPEAKER_04]: Taxes are now coming down.

669
00:44:53,197 --> 00:44:55,780
[SPEAKER_04]: The financial security that you want, I can deliver.

670
00:44:56,201 --> 00:45:01,127
[SPEAKER_04]: But if we put all that progress at risk with them, your family finances are going to get hammered.

671
00:45:01,147 --> 00:45:03,450
[SPEAKER_04]: Your taxes are going to get whacked up.

672
00:45:03,470 --> 00:45:05,052
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the choice for you at this election.

673
00:45:05,092 --> 00:45:07,114
[SPEAKER_04]: Do not surrender to their tax rises.

674
00:45:07,635 --> 00:45:07,695
[SPEAKER_10]: OK.

675
00:45:07,715 --> 00:45:08,196
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you both.

676
00:45:08,236 --> 00:45:15,625
[SPEAKER_10]: Just before we get to the next question, I'm going to remind everyone watching that we have got more questions coming in this prime ministerial debate.

677
00:45:15,725 --> 00:45:20,571
[SPEAKER_10]: But online on the BBC Live page, you'll be able to see what BBC verify

678
00:45:20,551 --> 00:45:27,480
[SPEAKER_10]: are already doing, they're already fact-checking and assessing the claims made here and will continue to do so throughout the time we are on air.

679
00:45:28,201 --> 00:45:30,303
[SPEAKER_10]: Our next question is from Robert Blackstock.

680
00:45:31,725 --> 00:45:32,646
[SPEAKER_00]: Good evening, gentlemen.

681
00:45:33,467 --> 00:45:40,836
[SPEAKER_00]: Mr Sunak, I think you made a fair job of being Chancellor, but you're a pretty mediocre Prime Minister.

682
00:45:42,218 --> 00:45:50,288
[SPEAKER_00]: Sakhir, I think that your strings are being pulled by very senior members of the Labour Party.

683
00:45:51,584 --> 00:46:09,559
[SPEAKER_00]: Are you two really the best we've got to be the next Prime Minister of our great country?

684
00:46:09,657 --> 00:46:15,955
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, Rob, look, I can understand your frustration, everyone's frustration, because the last few years have not been easy.

685
00:46:16,296 --> 00:46:17,700
[SPEAKER_04]: We've dealt with a lot as a country.

686
00:46:18,001 --> 00:46:19,284
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm not saying we've got everything right.

687
00:46:19,385 --> 00:46:21,390
[SPEAKER_04]: I certainly would be the first to acknowledge that.

688
00:46:21,752 --> 00:46:24,038
[SPEAKER_04]: But I've been your prime minister for 18 months.

689
00:46:24,119 --> 00:46:30,546
[SPEAKER_04]: And in that time, we've got inflation down from 11% with all the damage it was doing to the cost of living back to target.

690
00:46:30,827 --> 00:46:34,050
[SPEAKER_04]: The economy in the first quarter of this year, fastest growing in the G7.

691
00:46:34,491 --> 00:46:37,555
[SPEAKER_04]: Wages rising faster than prices for almost a year now.

692
00:46:37,815 --> 00:46:42,480
[SPEAKER_04]: And my primary job was to deliver that economic stability so I could start cutting your taxes.

693
00:46:42,781 --> 00:46:44,442
[SPEAKER_04]: That is the journey we're now on.

694
00:46:44,603 --> 00:46:48,808
[SPEAKER_04]: So whatever your other frustrations, the choice for you at this election is about the future.

695
00:46:49,308 --> 00:46:50,970
[SPEAKER_04]: If you want lower taxes,

696
00:46:50,950 --> 00:47:00,362
[SPEAKER_04]: If you want your borders secure, as Steve was asking before, if you want a sensible approach to net zero, if you want your pension protected with a triple lock plus, that is what I will D for you.

697
00:47:01,003 --> 00:47:04,728
[SPEAKER_04]: This is a serious election with consequences for you and your family.

698
00:47:05,068 --> 00:47:07,511
[SPEAKER_04]: I get the frustrations, but think about the choice.

699
00:47:07,771 --> 00:47:12,958
[SPEAKER_04]: Allow me to finish the job I've started, cut your taxes, protect your pension, secure our borders.

700
00:47:12,938 --> 00:47:24,965
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if Keir Starmer and the Labour Party are in charge, your taxes are going up, our borders are going to be insecure, you're going to be saddled with bills as he reverses my net zero changes, and every pensioner is going to face a retirement tax for the first time in history.

701
00:47:25,165 --> 00:47:27,771
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the choice that you should have in your mind.

702
00:47:27,871 --> 00:47:29,074
[SPEAKER_04]: Robert...

703
00:47:33,492 --> 00:47:51,904
[SPEAKER_03]: Robert, earlier in my career I worked in Northern Ireland with the police in Northern Ireland as part of the work out of the Good Friday Agreement and with a team I set out to change the police service in Northern Ireland to make sure it gained the confidence of all communities in Northern Ireland which was a really important part of the peace process.

704
00:47:51,924 --> 00:47:54,589
[SPEAKER_03]: So I went, I said what we would do and we delivered.

705
00:47:54,569 --> 00:47:59,115
[SPEAKER_03]: I then ran the Crown Prosecution Service for five years with 7,000 staff.

706
00:47:59,135 --> 00:48:02,139
[SPEAKER_03]: I said we would improve the way we dealt with violence against women and girls.

707
00:48:02,519 --> 00:48:03,220
[SPEAKER_03]: I said we'd do it.

708
00:48:03,260 --> 00:48:07,606
[SPEAKER_03]: We made the change, and we got on with it, and we made that change, and it was more successful at the end.

709
00:48:07,886 --> 00:48:22,905
[SPEAKER_03]: I came into the Labour Party to lead it four and a half years ago, and I said we will change our party to make sure that we are a party that can put a credible proposition before the country for changing the country, and that we'll always say, always say, country first, party second.

710
00:48:22,885 --> 00:48:24,887
[SPEAKER_03]: I've been there, I've done it, I've changed it.

711
00:48:25,127 --> 00:48:30,714
[SPEAKER_03]: What I'm now asking for is the opportunity to change our country for the better.

712
00:48:30,794 --> 00:48:32,936
[SPEAKER_03]: Because we've had 14 pretty awful years.

713
00:48:32,956 --> 00:48:37,982
[SPEAKER_03]: 14 years when I think most people would say we've ended up now with almost everything not working very well.

714
00:48:38,242 --> 00:48:41,245
[SPEAKER_03]: Worse than it was 14 years ago when this government came in.

715
00:48:41,586 --> 00:48:43,207
[SPEAKER_03]: Most people not feeling better off.

716
00:48:43,227 --> 00:48:44,609
[SPEAKER_03]: And this is a choice election.

717
00:48:44,909 --> 00:48:48,353
[SPEAKER_03]: Because if we go on for another five years of this under

718
00:48:48,333 --> 00:48:50,997
[SPEAKER_03]: that is not going to change.

719
00:48:51,177 --> 00:48:52,439
[SPEAKER_03]: That isn't going to change.

720
00:48:52,459 --> 00:49:07,962
[SPEAKER_03]: So this is the opportunity to turn the page, to rebuild our country, rebuild our public services, rebuild our economy and make sure that we can genuinely say to ourselves we're a better country, better run, proper public services and people feel better off.

721
00:49:07,942 --> 00:49:12,067
[SPEAKER_03]: I've done that sort of change throughout my life, and I'm asking for the opportunity to now do it for the country.

722
00:49:12,087 --> 00:49:17,053
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm just going to come back to the question, because I suspect that Robert Blackstock knows your background.

723
00:49:17,113 --> 00:49:19,817
[SPEAKER_10]: He certainly knows that you've been Chancellor.

724
00:49:19,857 --> 00:49:23,962
[SPEAKER_10]: He's probably familiar with your arguments, and he still says, are you two really the best?

725
00:49:24,002 --> 00:49:26,786
[SPEAKER_10]: We've got to be the next Prime Minister of our great country.

726
00:49:26,806 --> 00:49:31,271
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, polling does suggest that there's no great enthusiasm for either of you.

727
00:49:31,992 --> 00:49:32,993
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you recognise that?

728
00:49:33,013 --> 00:49:34,816
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you hear it on the campaign trail?

729
00:49:34,836 --> 00:49:35,957
[SPEAKER_10]: Are you aware of that?

730
00:49:35,937 --> 00:49:36,740
[SPEAKER_04]: Michelle, that's what I said.

731
00:49:37,222 --> 00:49:39,009
[SPEAKER_04]: I said to Rob, I recognise his frustrations.

732
00:49:39,029 --> 00:49:40,454
[SPEAKER_10]: It's more personal than that, isn't it?

733
00:49:40,474 --> 00:49:41,839
[SPEAKER_04]: He's talking about both of you.

734
00:49:42,120 --> 00:49:43,265
[SPEAKER_04]: But there's a choice for everyone.

735
00:49:44,188 --> 00:49:45,694
[SPEAKER_04]: There's a choice for everyone.

736
00:49:46,147 --> 00:49:47,589
[SPEAKER_04]: about change.

737
00:49:47,869 --> 00:49:51,514
[SPEAKER_04]: You don't get change unless you have a plan to deliver change.

738
00:49:51,534 --> 00:49:53,377
[SPEAKER_04]: Just saying it isn't going to bring about any change.

739
00:49:53,397 --> 00:50:00,486
[SPEAKER_04]: As you have heard tonight, there is no plan to cut your taxes, no plan to reform the welfare bill, no plan to deal with illegal migration.

740
00:50:00,686 --> 00:50:01,888
[SPEAKER_04]: That is the reality of it.

741
00:50:02,128 --> 00:50:02,949
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, there will be change.

742
00:50:02,989 --> 00:50:11,260
[SPEAKER_04]: It won't be change you like, it will be change when your taxes are going up, when we become the soft touch of Europe for illegal migrants, when pensioners are paying

743
00:50:11,240 --> 00:50:12,402
[SPEAKER_04]: tax for the first time.

744
00:50:12,702 --> 00:50:14,825
[SPEAKER_04]: That's the change that is coming.

745
00:50:15,046 --> 00:50:18,030
[SPEAKER_04]: So don't surrender to that, because your families are going to pay the price.

746
00:50:19,132 --> 00:50:31,289
[SPEAKER_03]: I think this question of enthusiasm is really important that you put to us, because I'm not surprised that after 14 years of this, people feel that the hope's been beaten out of them, because the country is in such a state.

747
00:50:31,309 --> 00:50:37,298
[SPEAKER_03]: They've had loads of promises made to them at the last election about what would happen, which haven't been delivered on.

748
00:50:37,278 --> 00:50:38,701
[SPEAKER_03]: and beat the hope out of people.

749
00:50:38,922 --> 00:50:42,209
[SPEAKER_03]: The very first question was about integrity in politics.

750
00:50:42,269 --> 00:50:44,213
[SPEAKER_03]: And again, people haven't seen that integrity.

751
00:50:44,373 --> 00:50:53,753
[SPEAKER_03]: You've had Partygate, you've had the breach of COVID rules, you've had the contracts for COVID, the instinct of some people to think the first thing in COVID I'm going to do is try to make money.

752
00:50:54,074 --> 00:50:57,902
[SPEAKER_03]: Same with the gambling commission nonsense over the last few weeks.

753
00:50:57,882 --> 00:51:01,767
[SPEAKER_03]: So this is an opportunity to restore that hope.

754
00:51:01,787 --> 00:51:06,773
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think we can do that by making grand promises of things that can't be delivered.

755
00:51:06,953 --> 00:51:10,117
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's the ordinary hope of working people.

756
00:51:10,217 --> 00:51:11,619
[SPEAKER_03]: My family was working class.

757
00:51:11,659 --> 00:51:18,047
[SPEAKER_03]: The ordinary hope of getting on yourself, getting on for your family, getting on for your community, and getting on for your country.

758
00:51:18,327 --> 00:51:24,034
[SPEAKER_03]: It has to be rooted, if we're going to restore hope, in my view, in returning politics to service.

759
00:51:24,435 --> 00:51:24,715
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

760
00:51:24,735 --> 00:51:27,298
[SPEAKER_03]: The sense that you come into politics to serve.

761
00:51:31,312 --> 00:51:34,538
[SPEAKER_10]: On that note, our next question, which is from Rachel Webster.

762
00:51:35,199 --> 00:51:35,700
[SPEAKER_01]: Good evening.

763
00:51:36,241 --> 00:51:41,871
[SPEAKER_01]: How can I ensure that if I vote for either of you two men, you'll put women's interests first?

764
00:51:47,462 --> 00:51:48,223
[SPEAKER_03]: Kirsten.

765
00:51:48,592 --> 00:51:50,995
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you very much for that question.

766
00:51:51,556 --> 00:51:59,746
[SPEAKER_03]: I have in my team, as partners with me, very, very good, strong women that will deliver for the country.

767
00:51:59,766 --> 00:52:04,432
[SPEAKER_03]: Rachel Reeves would be the first woman Chancellor if we're elected into government.

768
00:52:04,472 --> 00:52:12,422
[SPEAKER_03]: She worked, as you know, in the Bank of England and is very, very keen and strong on the fiscal rules and what we need to do for our economy.

769
00:52:12,402 --> 00:52:24,594
[SPEAKER_03]: I've got Angela Rayner, my deputy, who, again, has an incredible background, coming from a difficult background, where, you know, was a care worker for many years, and now deputy leader of my party.

770
00:52:24,614 --> 00:52:26,216
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm very proud of her.

771
00:52:26,396 --> 00:52:34,605
[SPEAKER_03]: And, you know, these people, and there are plenty of others, Yvette Cooper, Bridget Phillips, and you name it, really good, strong women who will be part of my team.

772
00:52:34,985 --> 00:52:40,030
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that leadership is about empowering your team and making sure it's a team on the pitch.

773
00:52:40,010 --> 00:52:42,432
[SPEAKER_03]: that are all batting and working together.

774
00:52:42,492 --> 00:53:10,000
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's the way I lead, not suggesting for a moment that I'm the one with all the answers, but knowing that if I lead my team and bring my team into this, and we work as a team and we'll serve as a team if we get the opportunity to do so, I will do it with some really fantastic, wonderful women who have been on this journey for me for four and a half years, changing our party to put it before the country with that, you know, essential principle, country first, party second.

775
00:53:10,385 --> 00:53:16,513
[SPEAKER_10]: Rishi Sunak, how would you ensure you'd put women's interests first?

776
00:53:16,593 --> 00:53:18,235
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so I didn't catch... Rachel.

777
00:53:18,255 --> 00:53:18,615
[SPEAKER_04]: Rachel.

778
00:53:19,076 --> 00:53:19,376
[SPEAKER_04]: Rachel.

779
00:53:19,877 --> 00:53:23,622
[SPEAKER_04]: You know, probably the easiest thing I can tell you is that I have two young daughters.

780
00:53:24,503 --> 00:53:34,215
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's why you can trust me, because as a dad, first and foremost, rather than a politician or prime minister, I want them to grow up in a country which is safe,

781
00:53:34,195 --> 00:53:43,107
[SPEAKER_04]: for them when they become teenagers and can walk around on their own, making sure that we have the right police on the streets, that our communities are safe for women and girls is really important to me.

782
00:53:43,127 --> 00:53:56,625
[SPEAKER_04]: I want to make sure that they have the health that they need and that's why we've been making changes to things like HRT and maternity care in hospitals, but I also want to make sure that when they grow up and have jobs and start a family that they're supported too.

783
00:53:56,605 --> 00:54:10,801
[SPEAKER_04]: which is why we're rolling out 30 hours of free childcare for every working parent from the time that their little one is nine months old to when the toddler goes off to school at four years, and that will make a big difference to families up and down the country.

784
00:54:11,582 --> 00:54:18,990
[SPEAKER_04]: But that's why I said, so I can go into lots more policies, but I want my girls to grow up in a country where the sky is the limit for their ambitions.

785
00:54:19,030 --> 00:54:24,216
[SPEAKER_04]: There is nothing that they can't do because they're women, and that's the kind of place that I believe in.

786
00:54:25,580 --> 00:54:32,969
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm going to bring in a related question because this came to us via the BBC's Your Voice, Your Vote website.

787
00:54:32,989 --> 00:54:44,464
[SPEAKER_10]: It was from Vicky in Oxfordshire who asks this, will you protect women's right to single sex spaces from any and all males regardless of if they hold a GRC, a gender recognition certificate?

788
00:54:44,524 --> 00:54:45,225
[SPEAKER_10]: Rishi Sunak?

789
00:54:45,205 --> 00:55:00,264
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, unequivocally, and we will do that by changing the law so that the Old Equalities Act recognises that sex means biological sex, and that will allow us to deliver on what Vicky wants, which is to protect female-only spaces, female-only services.

790
00:55:00,864 --> 00:55:07,973
[SPEAKER_04]: It's crystal clear for you there is a choice on that question at this election, because Keir Starmer is not matched

791
00:55:07,953 --> 00:55:10,457
[SPEAKER_04]: my pledge to reform the Equalities Act, to pass new law.

792
00:55:10,477 --> 00:55:13,142
[SPEAKER_04]: That is the only way to deliver on what Vicky says.

793
00:55:13,402 --> 00:55:23,660
[SPEAKER_04]: And the reason he won't do that, I don't know, but he can explain, is because he's not sure, like I am, that when it comes to these matters, sex means biological sex, and that's how you protect female-only spaces and services.

794
00:55:23,920 --> 00:55:24,561
[SPEAKER_10]: Keir Starmer?

795
00:55:29,468 --> 00:55:30,890
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes is the answer to the question.

796
00:55:31,371 --> 00:55:34,034
[SPEAKER_03]: It's very important that we protect women's spaces.

797
00:55:34,996 --> 00:55:39,262
[SPEAKER_03]: I saw this firsthand when I was Chief Prosecutor back in 2008-2013.

798
00:55:39,402 --> 00:55:50,197
[SPEAKER_03]: I was working with groups who were supportive of women who'd been subjected to domestic violence and sexual violence and saw for myself just how important it is to have those women's spaces.

799
00:55:50,478 --> 00:55:52,000
[SPEAKER_03]: Same in hospitals and

800
00:55:51,980 --> 00:55:53,262
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, in sport.

801
00:55:53,322 --> 00:55:55,505
[SPEAKER_03]: So, yes to that answer.

802
00:55:55,766 --> 00:56:09,787
[SPEAKER_03]: But what I will also say is that I do recognize that there are a small number of people who are born into a gender that they don't identify with, and I will treat them as I treat all human beings with dignity and respect.

803
00:56:09,807 --> 00:56:10,828
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'll tell you for why...

804
00:56:15,115 --> 00:56:15,976
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll tell you for why.

805
00:56:16,176 --> 00:56:18,780
[SPEAKER_03]: Because if you don't, you end up

806
00:56:19,503 --> 00:56:28,772
[SPEAKER_03]: the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom standing in Parliament making an anti-trans joke in front of the mother of a murdered trans teenager.

807
00:56:28,812 --> 00:56:37,901
[SPEAKER_03]: I will never, ever allow myself to be put into that position.

808
00:56:37,921 --> 00:56:38,722
[SPEAKER_04]: That's not what I did.

809
00:56:38,762 --> 00:56:41,845
[SPEAKER_04]: I was pointing out that you've changed your mind on this question multiple times.

810
00:56:41,925 --> 00:56:45,729
[SPEAKER_04]: But to answer Vicky's question, you can't deliver on what Vicky wants.

811
00:56:45,749 --> 00:56:49,493
[SPEAKER_04]: So everyone who does want female spaces protected

812
00:56:50,047 --> 00:56:55,976
[SPEAKER_04]: has to be prepared to change the laws that the Equalities Act recognizes that sex means biological sex.

813
00:56:55,996 --> 00:56:57,178
[SPEAKER_04]: It's pretty straightforward.

814
00:56:57,558 --> 00:57:01,104
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, Keir Starmer says that he believes in that, but he won't change the law to do it.

815
00:57:01,164 --> 00:57:02,666
[SPEAKER_04]: So he's not being straight with you again.

816
00:57:03,127 --> 00:57:08,415
[SPEAKER_04]: By saying one thing and doing another, you won't change the law to recognize that sex means biological sex.

817
00:57:08,435 --> 00:57:14,704
[SPEAKER_04]: So you cannot say to Vicky and everyone else who cares about this issue that you will actually ensure that their spaces are protected.

818
00:57:14,887 --> 00:57:23,276
[SPEAKER_03]: If he'd been in as many support centers that I've been in for those that have survived sexual violence and domestic violence, he would know very well it is possible to do it.

819
00:57:23,336 --> 00:57:24,137
[SPEAKER_03]: It is being done.

820
00:57:24,197 --> 00:57:26,560
[SPEAKER_03]: I've supported it being done when I was chief prosecutor.

821
00:57:26,780 --> 00:57:29,123
[SPEAKER_03]: I've always believed in that principle of women's spaces.

822
00:57:29,764 --> 00:57:42,598
[SPEAKER_03]: That's by going back to 2008, way before this latest iteration of the debate, because I could recognize for myself just how important it was to have that space, women-only space, biological women-only space,

823
00:57:42,578 --> 00:57:46,104
[SPEAKER_03]: particularly in that area, but also in other areas.

824
00:57:46,324 --> 00:57:47,286
[SPEAKER_10]: How do you ensure it?

825
00:57:47,326 --> 00:57:47,847
[SPEAKER_10]: Just a second.

826
00:57:47,867 --> 00:57:51,353
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, Rishi Sunak, how do you ensure it without changing the Equality Act?

827
00:57:51,373 --> 00:57:52,815
[SPEAKER_03]: It's provided for under the Equality Act.

828
00:57:52,835 --> 00:57:56,582
[SPEAKER_03]: It is actually spelled out as one of the examples given in the Act.

829
00:57:56,642 --> 00:57:57,904
[SPEAKER_03]: It always has been.

830
00:57:58,137 --> 00:58:07,269
[SPEAKER_03]: and fabricating a difference here in a situation where actually we should be trying to find common ground and work together.

831
00:58:07,829 --> 00:58:10,513
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I'm proud of the record of my party on women's rights.

832
00:58:10,533 --> 00:58:16,941
[SPEAKER_03]: We've done amazing things in terms of equality under Labour governments, made a massive difference to millions of lives.

833
00:58:17,101 --> 00:58:20,786
[SPEAKER_03]: There's much more work to do on women's equality going forward.

834
00:58:20,986 --> 00:58:24,010
[SPEAKER_03]: But the only way I think we can make that progress

835
00:58:23,990 --> 00:58:38,590
[SPEAKER_03]: is if we change the way that we do politics, stop this business of always trying to divide everybody and actually use the opportunity of leadership, which is what I would do, to say the job of the leader of the country is to bring people together.

836
00:58:38,630 --> 00:58:44,378
[SPEAKER_03]: These are difficult discussions, different opinions of course, but the role of the leader of the country

837
00:58:44,358 --> 00:58:49,124
[SPEAKER_03]: is to bring that together so that the country itself is less divided.

838
00:58:49,144 --> 00:59:06,484
[SPEAKER_03]: One of the issues for me is the, with sadness, is the fact that over the last 14 years there's been this tendency on almost every issue to try to find the points of difference and division rather than doing what we're actually really good at as a country, which is bringing people together.

839
00:59:11,122 --> 00:59:14,606
[SPEAKER_04]: This is about the courage of your convictions and principles.

840
00:59:15,507 --> 00:59:19,731
[SPEAKER_04]: I believe when it comes to these matters, sex means biological sex.

841
00:59:19,751 --> 00:59:24,937
[SPEAKER_04]: Of course, we should have compassion and tolerance for people who are going through questioning that.

842
00:59:24,957 --> 00:59:30,623
[SPEAKER_04]: But fundamentally, when it comes to women's safety, women's only spaces, sex means biological sex for me.

843
00:59:30,803 --> 00:59:35,188
[SPEAKER_04]: That is the only way to make sure you can deliver the protections that Vicky wants.

844
00:59:35,168 --> 00:59:43,255
[SPEAKER_04]: And on this question, Keir Starmer, when one of his own female MPs made that point a while ago, he said that she was wrong.

845
00:59:44,500 --> 00:59:46,122
[SPEAKER_04]: She was hounded, right?

846
00:59:46,142 --> 00:59:47,184
[SPEAKER_04]: He said she was wrong.

847
00:59:47,224 --> 00:59:52,451
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, he's now changed his mind on that question, that it goes back to trust, it goes back to having the courage of your convictions.

848
00:59:52,731 --> 00:59:55,615
[SPEAKER_04]: I get that not all of you will agree with my position, right?

849
00:59:55,635 --> 00:59:56,536
[SPEAKER_04]: But I'm being clear with you.

850
00:59:57,077 --> 00:59:58,379
[SPEAKER_04]: Sex means biological sex.

851
00:59:58,639 --> 01:00:02,945
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to change the Equalities Act to deliver the security of women's spaces and women's services.

852
01:00:03,025 --> 01:00:05,188
[SPEAKER_04]: That's what I believe the right thing for our country is.

853
01:00:05,288 --> 01:00:09,254
[SPEAKER_10]: And if you don't agree with that last part, that's what I will do.

854
01:00:09,274 --> 01:00:10,255
[SPEAKER_10]: Which relates to one of your MPs, Rosie Duffield.

855
01:00:11,332 --> 01:00:14,638
[SPEAKER_03]: The Prime Minister knows perfectly well that this is already set out in the Equalities Act already.

856
01:00:14,658 --> 01:00:17,724
[SPEAKER_03]: The specific instance of safe spaces is set out.

857
01:00:17,804 --> 01:00:18,846
[SPEAKER_03]: Read the legislation.

858
01:00:18,866 --> 01:00:20,329
[SPEAKER_03]: Look at the notes under the legislation.

859
01:00:20,349 --> 01:00:21,411
[SPEAKER_03]: It's been there for years.

860
01:00:21,811 --> 01:00:26,019
[SPEAKER_03]: Don't just use this as a political football to try to divide people across the country.

861
01:00:26,039 --> 01:00:26,219
[SPEAKER_10]: OK.

862
01:00:26,239 --> 01:00:27,081
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you very much for that.

863
01:00:27,141 --> 01:00:29,866
[SPEAKER_10]: We will move on to our next question.

864
01:00:29,886 --> 01:00:31,990
[SPEAKER_10]: And this one is from Judy Waters.

865
01:00:33,809 --> 01:00:34,852
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening, gents.

866
01:00:35,333 --> 01:00:38,462
[SPEAKER_08]: I own a jazz vinyl record business with my partner.

867
01:00:39,385 --> 01:00:43,176
[SPEAKER_08]: Post Brexit, we have lost 90% of our business with Europe.

868
01:00:43,878 --> 01:00:47,548
[SPEAKER_08]: How can we mend our broken trading relationship with Europe?

869
01:00:51,308 --> 01:00:55,419
[SPEAKER_10]: 90% of Julie's business with Europe has been lost.

870
01:00:55,479 --> 01:00:57,043
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Keir Starmer, you were a Remainer.

871
01:00:57,063 --> 01:00:59,730
[SPEAKER_10]: Rishi Sunak, you argued and voted for leave.

872
01:01:00,090 --> 01:01:03,218
[SPEAKER_10]: How can we mend our broken trading relationship with Europe?

873
01:01:03,499 --> 01:01:06,567
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, Julie, first of all, thank you for doing what you do.

874
01:01:06,547 --> 01:01:08,310
[SPEAKER_04]: My mum was also a small business owner.

875
01:01:08,410 --> 01:01:10,353
[SPEAKER_04]: I grew up in a family that had a family business.

876
01:01:10,494 --> 01:01:11,435
[SPEAKER_04]: I know how hard it is.

877
01:01:11,836 --> 01:01:13,078
[SPEAKER_04]: I know what the struggles are like.

878
01:01:13,318 --> 01:01:15,502
[SPEAKER_04]: And our economy is built on people like you.

879
01:01:15,943 --> 01:01:19,930
[SPEAKER_04]: And you deserve all our support and admiration and praise for doing what you are doing.

880
01:01:20,030 --> 01:01:21,973
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry things have been difficult.

881
01:01:21,953 --> 01:01:27,579
[SPEAKER_04]: We had the referendum, and now our focus should be on making sure we make the best of all the opportunities.

882
01:01:28,079 --> 01:01:32,643
[SPEAKER_04]: In an economy-wide sense, we're actually doing very well now at exporting around the world.

883
01:01:32,904 --> 01:01:36,848
[SPEAKER_04]: But in order to help you, I have two specific things that I can do that will help.

884
01:01:37,408 --> 01:01:40,431
[SPEAKER_04]: One of them is to make sure that we cut your taxes on business rates.

885
01:01:40,491 --> 01:01:47,438
[SPEAKER_04]: When I talk to small retailers like yours, I think you said you had a premises, the thing that everyone talks to me about is business rates.

