935
01:04:54,418 --> 01:04:58,782
[SPEAKER_03]: We're not rejoining the single market or the customs union, and we're not accepting freedom of movement.

936
01:04:58,802 --> 01:04:59,843
[SPEAKER_03]: But I'm not a defeatist.

937
01:04:59,903 --> 01:05:01,564
[SPEAKER_04]: Will you accept free migration in any form?

938
01:05:01,584 --> 01:05:03,726
[SPEAKER_03]: Please, let me finish answering the question.

939
01:05:03,746 --> 01:05:07,069
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not a defeatist like the Prime Minister who says to Julie, bad luck.

940
01:05:07,049 --> 01:05:08,593
[SPEAKER_03]: That's as good as it gets.

941
01:05:08,613 --> 01:05:11,360
[SPEAKER_03]: You'll have to go along with the problems you've got, however hard that is for you.

942
01:05:11,580 --> 01:05:12,122
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not in that.

943
01:05:12,142 --> 01:05:16,352
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not going to say to you, Julie, there's nothing I can do to help you or to other people in the same position.

944
01:05:16,673 --> 01:05:21,545
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm going to say, I know we can get a better deal than the botched deal that we've got, and I'm going to go out and fight for it.

945
01:05:21,685 --> 01:05:23,590
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not going to have freedom of movement come back.

946
01:05:23,570 --> 01:05:34,820
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not going to go back into the EU, but I'm going to fight for a better deal so you can trade more easily across Europe, so you can succeed, and our economy can succeed, because I believe in our country.

947
01:05:34,980 --> 01:05:48,873
[SPEAKER_04]: In the 18 months I've had the job, I've negotiated with the EU for the Windsor Framework, restored the government in Northern Ireland and strengthened our union, made sure that we are part of the horizon scheme on positive terms, warmly welcomed by the entire research community or universities.

948
01:05:49,073 --> 01:05:51,535
[SPEAKER_04]: I've got a track record of doing those deals with the EU.

949
01:05:51,936 --> 01:05:53,577
[SPEAKER_04]: But you just say you'll get a deal.

950
01:05:53,557 --> 01:05:54,959
[SPEAKER_04]: What will it cost?

951
01:05:55,000 --> 01:05:56,041
[SPEAKER_04]: You're not being straight with people.

952
01:05:56,202 --> 01:05:56,542
[SPEAKER_04]: I know.

953
01:05:56,582 --> 01:05:58,626
[SPEAKER_04]: What it will cost is more migration.

954
01:05:58,886 --> 01:05:59,988
[SPEAKER_04]: He's not being straight with you.

955
01:06:00,128 --> 01:06:04,536
[SPEAKER_04]: You think it's just magic, magic, some good thing for us, and they won't want something in return, right?

956
01:06:04,556 --> 01:06:06,199
[SPEAKER_04]: It's just, again, you're taking people for fools.

957
01:06:06,419 --> 01:06:07,461
[SPEAKER_04]: They've been crystal clear.

958
01:06:07,481 --> 01:06:10,346
[SPEAKER_04]: The price of any of those things is greater migration.

959
01:06:10,727 --> 01:06:12,189
[SPEAKER_04]: It is fundamental to how they think about it.

960
01:06:12,209 --> 01:06:17,218
[SPEAKER_10]: Do you accept, Keir Starmer, if you were the Prime Minister, you would have to give something in return for the kind of deal you want with Europe?

961
01:06:17,198 --> 01:06:21,163
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, but I think it's very important when you start those negotiations, you're very clear the lines you won't cross.

962
01:06:21,463 --> 01:06:23,485
[SPEAKER_03]: And I've just set out the lines that I won't cross.

963
01:06:23,525 --> 01:06:26,449
[SPEAKER_03]: But I'm not a defeatist like the Prime Minister, and nor will I say to Julie...

964
01:06:26,469 --> 01:06:31,215
[SPEAKER_03]: I won't insult Julie by saying, it's all fine, everything's working, everything's great.

965
01:06:31,475 --> 01:06:41,687
[SPEAKER_03]: Part of the problem we have with this Prime Minister is that his lived world is millions of miles away from the lived worlds of individuals across the country, the businesses and the families that they're trying to support.

966
01:06:41,747 --> 01:06:43,909
[SPEAKER_03]: There's a massive gap.

967
01:06:43,930 --> 01:06:44,370
[SPEAKER_03]: That is a problem.

968
01:06:45,177 --> 01:06:50,525
[SPEAKER_04]: And again, you just won't rule out, will you accept any greater migration as the price of a deal with the EU?

969
01:06:50,545 --> 01:06:51,046
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes or no?

970
01:06:51,266 --> 01:06:51,767
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I don't.

971
01:06:52,248 --> 01:06:57,075
[SPEAKER_03]: But I would say this, that migration, lawful migration, is at record numbers under this Prime Minister.

972
01:06:57,255 --> 01:07:01,682
[SPEAKER_03]: He's actually the most liberal Prime Minister we've ever had when it comes to immigration.

973
01:07:01,762 --> 01:07:03,424
[SPEAKER_03]: The numbers have gone through the roof.

974
01:07:03,785 --> 01:07:06,950
[SPEAKER_03]: They're actually far higher than they were when we were in the EU.

975
01:07:07,250 --> 01:07:11,116
[SPEAKER_03]: So I really don't think you can start lecturing other people about higher migration.

976
01:07:11,156 --> 01:07:13,800
[SPEAKER_03]: They've never been as high as they are on your watch.

977
01:07:13,780 --> 01:07:16,704
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, what I can do is point out the choice for everyone at this election.

978
01:07:17,165 --> 01:07:21,451
[SPEAKER_04]: This year, because of the actions I've taken, the number of visas we've issued is down by 30%.

979
01:07:21,711 --> 01:07:27,320
[SPEAKER_04]: Net migration is forecast to halve in just the next 12 months because of the measures I've taken, because it was too high.

980
01:07:27,540 --> 01:07:30,544
[SPEAKER_04]: But I've been Prime Minister for 18 months, now it's coming down sharply.

981
01:07:31,185 --> 01:07:37,975
[SPEAKER_04]: That's a progress we'll continue if I'm your Prime Minister, and we'll have a legal cap in Parliament to guarantee the numbers keep falling after that.

982
01:07:38,155 --> 01:07:41,560
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, if Keir Starmer's your Prime Minister, you won't get any of that.

983
01:07:41,540 --> 01:07:45,687
[SPEAKER_04]: Because he opposes those changes, he won't have a legal cap on migration, and it will go up.

984
01:07:46,448 --> 01:07:48,171
[SPEAKER_04]: So that's a choice for your legal migration.

985
01:07:48,211 --> 01:07:50,334
[SPEAKER_04]: Continue the progress we've made underneath.

986
01:07:50,354 --> 01:07:54,080
[SPEAKER_04]: It's forecast to half, legal cap in Parliament, or open borders.

987
01:07:54,140 --> 01:07:55,763
[SPEAKER_04]: Surrender your borders to the Labour Party.

988
01:07:55,783 --> 01:07:56,644
[SPEAKER_04]: He's making it up as he goes along.

989
01:07:56,704 --> 01:07:59,008
[SPEAKER_04]: He's making it up as he goes along.

990
01:07:58,988 --> 01:08:00,590
[SPEAKER_10]: And in here... Actually, hang on.

991
01:08:00,610 --> 01:08:03,513
[SPEAKER_05]: Our next question... No, I'm going to the... No, I'm going to the next question.

992
01:08:03,533 --> 01:08:04,874
[SPEAKER_05]: You get BBC verified to check.

993
01:08:04,894 --> 01:08:06,095
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm going to the next question.

